{"title_page": "Tribute (1980 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1980 film by Bob Clark}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Tribute\n| image\t         = Tribute FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Bob Clark]]\n| producer       = [[Garth Drabinsky]]<br>[[Joel B. Michaels]]\n| writer         = [[Bernard Slade]]\n| based_on = ''[[Tribute (play)|Tribute]]'' <br>by Bernard Slade\n| starring       = [[Jack Lemmon]]<br>[[Lee Remick]]<br>[[Robby Benson]]\n| music          = [[Kenneth Wannberg]]\n| cinematography = Reginald H. Morris\n| editing        = Richard Halsey\n| studio = Tiberius Films<br>The Turman-Foster Company\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = 14 December 1980\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $8 million<ref>Aubrey Solomon, ''Twentieth Century Fox: A Corporate and Financial History'', Scarecrow Press, 1989 p259</ref>\n| gross = $4 million (US/ Canada)<ref>Solomon p 235. Figures are rentals not total gross.</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Tribute''''' is a 1980 Canadian [[comedy drama|comedy-drama film]] directed by [[Bob Clark]] and starring [[Jack Lemmon]] as Scottie Templeton, a terminally-ill [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] agent trying to make amends with his family and friends. [[Robby Benson]] and [[Lee Remick]] co-star, with supporting roles [[Colleen Dewhurst]], [[John Marley]], [[Kim Cattrall]], and [[Gale Garnett]]. It is based on the play of the [[Tribute (play)|same name]] by [[Bernard Slade]], who also wrote the screenplay. \n\nThe film was released in December 1980 to widespread critical acclaim. It was entered into the [[31st Berlin International Film Festival]] where Jack Lemmon won the [[Silver Bear for Best Actor]], and Clark was nominated for the [[Golden Bear]].<ref name=\"berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1981/03_preistr_ger_1981/03_Preistraeger_1981.html |title=Berlinale 1981: Prize Winners |accessdate=2010-08-31 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> Lemmon was also nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]] and a [[Golden Globe]] for his performance, and won the [[Genie Awards|Genie Award]] for [[Genie Award for Best Performance by a Foreign Actor|Best Performance by a Foreign Actor]]. The film was nominated for ten other Genies, including [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Picture]], [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Director|Best Direction]], [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]], and [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Original Score|Best Score]].\n\n==Plot==\nScottie Templeton is a show-business veteran, based in New York and well known in the theatrical community there. He has many acquaintances, but is divorced from his wife and estranged from his only son.\n\nScottie learns that he has [[leukemia]] and is dying. His ex-wife Maggie, in town for a school reunion, comes to visit and reflect on their time together. Scottie makes an effort to reconnect with his son, Jud, who still has anger issues. A young actress Scottie once dated, Sally Haines, strikes Scottie as someone who might be a good romantic match for his son. As a testimonial dinner is organized in Scottie's honor, he attempts to repair some of his past relationships in the time he has left.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Jack Lemmon]] - Scottie Templeton\n* [[Robby Benson]] - Jud Templeton\n* [[Lee Remick]] - Maggie Stratton\n* [[Colleen Dewhurst]] - Gladys Petrelli\n* [[John Marley]] - Lou Daniels\n* [[Kim Cattrall]] - Sally Haines\n* [[Gale Garnett]] - Hilary\n* [[Teri Keane]] - Evelyn\n* Rummy Bishop - Poker Player\n* John Dee - Poker Player\n* Bob Windsor - Poker Player\n* Eileen Lehman - Nurse\n* Andrew Foot - Actor\n* Trevor Daley - Cop\n\n==Awards==\nIt was entered into the [[31st Berlin International Film Festival]] where [[Jack Lemmon]] won the [[Silver Bear for Best Actor]].<ref name=\"berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1981/03_preistr_ger_1981/03_Preistraeger_1981.html |title=Berlinale 1981: Prize Winners |accessdate=2010-08-31 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> Lemmon was also nominated for a [[Golden Globe]] and an [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]] for his performance. He won the Canadian [[Genie Awards|Genie Award]] for [[Genie Award for Best Performance by a Foreign Actor|Best Performance by a Foreign Actor]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0081656|title=Tribute}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|1022007_tribute}}\n*{{Mojo title|tribute}}\n\n{{Bob Clark}}\n\n[[Category:1980 films]]\n[[Category:1980s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about cancer]]\n[[Category:Films based on Canadian plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bob Clark]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n\n\n{{1980s-Canada-film-stub}}\n{{1980s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1980 film by Bob Clark}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Tribute\n| image\t         = Tribute FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Bob Clark]]\n| producer       = [[Garth Drabinsky]]<br>[[Joel B. Michaels]]\n| writer         = [[Bernard Slade]]\n| based_on = ''[[Tribute (play)|Tribute]]'' <br>by Bernard Slade\n| starring       = [[Jack Lemmon]]<br>[[Lee Remick]]<br>[[Robby Benson]]\n| music          = [[Kenneth Wannberg]]\n| cinematography = Reginald H. Morris\n| editing        = Richard Halsey\n| studio = Tiberius Films<br>The Turman-Foster Company\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = 14 December 1980\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $8 million<ref>Aubrey Solomon, ''Twentieth Century Fox: A Corporate and Financial History'', Scarecrow Press, 1989 p259</ref>\n| gross = $4 million (US/ Canada)<ref>Solomon p 235. Figures are rentals not total gross.</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Tribute''''' is a 1980 Canadian [[comedy drama|comedy-drama film]] directed by [[Bob Clark]] and starring [[Jack Lemmon]] as Scottie Templeton, a terminally-ill [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] agent trying to make amends with his family and friends. [[Robby Benson]] and [[Lee Remick]] co-star, with supporting roles [[Colleen Dewhurst]], [[John Marley]], [[Kim Cattrall]], and [[Gale Garnett]]. It is based on the play of the [[Tribute (play)|same name]] by [[Bernard Slade]], who also wrote the screenplay. \n\nThe film was released in December 1980 to widespread critical acclaim. It was entered into the [[31st Berlin International Film Festival]] where Jack Lemmon won the [[Silver Bear for Best Actor]], and Clark was nominated for the [[Golden Bear]].<ref name=\"berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1981/03_preistr_ger_1981/03_Preistraeger_1981.html |title=Berlinale 1981: Prize Winners |accessdate=2010-08-31 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> Lemmon was also nominated for a [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe]] and an [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]] for his performance, and won the [[Genie Awards|Genie Award]] for [[Genie Award for Best Performance by a Foreign Actor|Best Performance by a Foreign Actor]]. The film was nominated for ten other Genies, including [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Picture]], [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Director|Best Direction]], [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]], and [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Original Score|Best Score]].\n\n==Plot==\nScottie Templeton is a show-business veteran, based in New York and well known in the theatrical community there. He has many acquaintances, but is divorced from his wife and estranged from his only son.\n\nScottie learns that he has [[leukemia]] and is dying. His ex-wife Maggie, in town for a school reunion, comes to visit and reflect on their time together. Scottie makes an effort to reconnect with his son, Jud, who still has anger issues. A young actress Scottie once dated, Sally Haines, strikes Scottie as someone who might be a good romantic match for his son. As a testimonial dinner is organized in Scottie's honor, he attempts to repair some of his past relationships in the time he has left.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Jack Lemmon]] - Scottie Templeton\n* [[Robby Benson]] - Jud Templeton\n* [[Lee Remick]] - Maggie Stratton\n* [[Colleen Dewhurst]] - Gladys Petrelli\n* [[John Marley]] - Lou Daniels\n* [[Kim Cattrall]] - Sally Haines\n* [[Gale Garnett]] - Hilary\n* [[Teri Keane]] - Evelyn\n* Rummy Bishop - Poker Player\n* John Dee - Poker Player\n* Bob Windsor - Poker Player\n* Eileen Lehman - Nurse\n* Andrew Foot - Actor\n* Trevor Daley - Cop\n\n==Awards==\nIt was entered into the [[31st Berlin International Film Festival]] where [[Jack Lemmon]] won the [[Silver Bear for Best Actor]].<ref name=\"berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1981/03_preistr_ger_1981/03_Preistraeger_1981.html |title=Berlinale 1981: Prize Winners |accessdate=2010-08-31 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> Lemmon was also nominated for a [[Golden Globe]] and an [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]] for his performance. He won the Canadian [[Genie Awards|Genie Award]] for [[Genie Award for Best Performance by a Foreign Actor|Best Performance by a Foreign Actor]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0081656|title=Tribute}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|1022007_tribute}}\n*{{Mojo title|tribute}}\n\n{{Bob Clark}}\n\n[[Category:1980 films]]\n[[Category:1980s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about cancer]]\n[[Category:Film